=========================================
C++ LAMBDA EXPRESSIONS (C++11)
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is a lambda?
---------------------
A lambda is an anonymous function (no name function)
used for short inline operations.

It is mostly used with STL algorithms.

-----------------------------------------

2. Basic Syntax
---------------

auto f = [capture](parameters) -> return_type {
    // body
};

Example:
auto add = [](int a, int b) -> int {
    return a + b;
};

cout << add(2, 3);

-----------------------------------------

3. Lambda Parts
---------------

[capture]     -> captures external variables
(parameters)   -> input arguments
-> return type -> optional
{ body }       -> function logic

-----------------------------------------

4. Capture Types (IMPORTANT)
----------------------------

[]      -> captures nothing
[=]     -> captures all variables by VALUE
[&]     -> captures all variables by REFERENCE

[x]     -> captures x by value
[&x]    -> captures x by reference

[=, &x] -> default value capture, x by reference
[&, x]  -> default reference capture, x by value

-----------------------------------------

5. Mutable Lambda
------------------

By default, captured-by-value variables are const.

mutable allows modification:

int x = 10;

auto f = [x]() mutable {
    x += 5;
    return x;
};

-----------------------------------------

6. Lambda with std::function
-----------------------------

#include <functional>

std::function<int(int,int)> f =
[](int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
};

-----------------------------------------

7. Common Use Cases
-------------------

- STL algorithms (for_each, sort, find_if)
- Short callbacks
- Custom comparators
- Event handling logic

Example:
for_each(v.begin(), v.end(),
[](int x){ cout << x << " "; });

-----------------------------------------

8. Example (Practical)
----------------------

vector<int> v = {1,2,3,4};

int sum = 0;

for_each(v.begin(), v.end(),
[&](int x) { sum += x; });

cout << sum;

-----------------------------------------

9. Why use lambda?
------------------

✔ Cleaner code
✔ No need to define separate function
✔ Best for STL algorithms
✔ Improves readability for small logic

-----------------------------------------

